David,

I think the point you are missing that we are trying to say is this is not like Newtonian physics.  This line
of study is more like quantum physics.  You are going to get different results based on the observer and
 possibly even the expectation of a result.  We are in the realm of mind and perception here.

Also I don&#39;t recall anyone saying that these things (whatever they are) **have** to fit in a microwave, just that it
was in interesting experiment.

Don




________________________________



-- &quot;David Koenig&quot; &lt;floridajakeblues@ gmail.com&gt; wrote:

Well AL 

I don&#39;t claim to have all the answers. In my world &quot;I don&#39;t have to be right.&quot;

If you have all of the answers &quot;For Sure&quot; then thanks for sharing. It will save me a lot of critical thinking.

Otherwise I will continue to use the Scientific methods of reason and observation.


